message.content:
The only way to begin a derivation from the start symbol is  

S ⇒ NT97 NT1                     (the only rule for S)  

NT97 can only produce the single terminal t75, so the first token of the
string must be t75 – which it is.

Thus the remainder of the string (tokens 2‑19) has to be generated by NT1.

NT1 has just two possibilities  

1. NT1 ⇒ 't178'                         (one single terminal)  
2. NT1 ⇒ NT61 NT192                   

The substring to be generated contains 18 tokens, so alternative 1 is
impossible; we must use alternative 2 and split the 18‑token suffix into a
prefix produced by NT61 and a suffix produced by NT192.

NT61 can be expanded only as  

a) NT61 ⇒ NT18 NT177  
b) NT61 ⇒ NT51 NT131  

Expansion (b) is impossible because the very next token is t105, not the
t104 required by NT51.  Therefore we need expansion (a):

token 2  must be produced by NT18 (NT18 → t105), which is indeed t105.  
After that, the rest of NT61 has to be generated by NT177.

But NT177 has only two rules  

NT177 ⇒ NT73 NT151  
NT177 ⇒ NT4  NT114

• The second rule would require the next two tokens to be t132 (NT4) and
  t92 (NT114), leaving sixteen tokens still to be covered by NT192.  
  NT192, however, can expand only as NT140 NT152; its left component
  NT140 can produce at most two tokens (either t112 or t27 t137).  
  No possible way remains for NT152 to cover the fourteen or fifteen
  tokens that would still be left.

• The first rule would require the final symbol (NT151) to be either t182
  or t196, but those terminals do not occur anywhere in the substring.

Hence NT177 cannot generate the required portion of the string, so NT61
cannot generate it, so NT1 cannot, and therefore S cannot.

Consequently the given grammar does not generate the string.

No
